Part 2

Goal

In this section, I aim to build a predictive model that estimates a point guards salary using only their on-court statistics from that season. The goal is to identify players who may be overpaid or underpaid relative to their production and explore how well statistical performance alone can explain salary differences. While I recognize that salary is influenced by many external factorssuch as team success, roster construction, and player reputationthis model will focus only on what Ive been analyzing throughout Part 1. This decision aligns with the scope of data I have access to and allows for a more controlled evaluation of point guard value.

Ultimately, this is meant to be one of several small, focused NBA projects where I build and apply analytics tools to better understand trends around player evaluation. Im excited to see what insights emerge and would love any feedback on how to make these models stronger or more informative. My contact information and past work can be found on my personal website.

Data Preperation and Modeling Approach

To begin the modeling process, I continued using the same player-level data from Part 1, pulling from Basketball Reference. I filtered the data down to point guards only from the 201920 through 202425 seasons, applying minimum thresholds for games played and minutes to ensure only reliable samples were included. Each players stats were aggregated per season, and I joined shooting, advanced, and overall player performance metrics into a single dataset. These included stats like usage rate, true shooting percentage, assist rate, shot location efficiency, and more, all of which were featured in my earlier analysis.

The models are trained using a standard 80/20 split, where 80% of the data is used for training and the remaining 20% for testing. My modeling strategy is based on linear regression, using season-level data to predict a players salary for that year. I experimented with three versions: one predicting raw salary directly, another using the log-transformed salary, and another using percentile rank of salary as the target,. To improve robustness, I cleaned the training set by removing high-leverage and high-influence points, as well as extreme outliers based on standardized residuals and Cooks distance.

For each model I tested, I used subset selection techniquesboth forward and backwardto identify combinations of predictors that performed best using adjusted R and mean absolute error (MAE) as my primary evaluation metrics. In addition to traditional summary statistics, I assessed model quality visually with residual plots and predicted vs.actual comparisons. These steps helped ensure that the final model wasnt overfit and retained strong interpretability while still explaining as much variation in salary as possible.

Model 1 - Raw Salary

The first model I built aimed to predict raw annual salary using traditional linear regression and player-level stats from each season. I included a range of shooting and advanced metrics based on their earlier correlation with salary and then used backward and forward selection to settle on a final formula. The resulting model, prior to cleaning for outliers, is shown below:

Salary =173.533 + 8.958 OBPM 10.405 Age 25.192 USG%
+ 0.022 POSS + 394.208 FGA% (16ft3P) 62.086 FGA% (2PT) + 164.383 FTAr
+ 177.362 FG% (310 ft) 1.089 FG% (3PT) + 49.616 %Assisted 2PT 236.143 FG% (2PT)
+ 19.569 BLK% + 3.167 TOV% + 1.128 Age USG%

Coefficients rounded to predict Salary in $100,000s

Before removing outliers, the model achieved a mean absolute error of $4,975,009 on the test set and an adjusted R of 0.712. After filtering out high-leverage and high-influence observations using standardized residuals and Cooks distance, the cleaned model showed a slightly higher mean absolute error of $5,196,012, but improved fit with an adjusted R of 0.81. This suggests the refined model better explains the overall variance in the data despite being slightly less accurate on unseen examples. The cleaned model more effectively captured key statistical relationships, especially those involving Offensive Box Plus-Minus (OBPM), Usage Rate (USG%), and three-point shooting efficiency, while reducing the influence of extreme cases. For reference the equation to the model without outliers is below:

While the cleaned model sacrifices a small amount of predictive accuracy on unseen data, it offers a clearer and more statistically consistent view of how specific metrics relate to salary. The relationship between predicted and actual salary values is visualized below to further illustrate the models performance.


The plot above shows that the cleaned model does a solid job predicting player salary based solely on statistical output, particularly for some of those mid-range contracts. While some variance remainsespecially among the leagues lower earning point guardsits clear the model captures many of the core factors driving compensation. One limitation, however, is that the model predicts a salary of $0 for a small number of players. This likely reflects statistical profiles that fall well outside the norm, while not being considered outliers, and may warrant a closer look to confirm whether those players are true point guards and what specific metrics are driving their predicted value so low. This version provides a useful benchmark for comparison as I now explore alternate modeling strategies, starting with a log-transformed salary approach.

Model 2 - Logarithmic Salary

For the second modeling approach, I applied a natural log transformation to player salary in an effort to reduce skew and stabilize the variance in residuals. NBA salary data is highly right-skewed due to the presence of several max-level contracts, which can heavily influence linear regression models. By modeling log(salary) instead of raw salary, the regression better captures proportional changes and is less sensitive to extreme outliers. This is a common approach when dealing with salary, income, or other growth-based financial variables.

The uncleaned model achieved a mean absolute error of $7,155,602 on the test set. After removing high-leverage and high-influence points using residual diagnostics, the cleaned model improved performance with a reduced error of $6,367,144. Its important to note that while the model predicts log(salary), I exponentiate the predictions to convert them back to actual salary values for evaluation and comparison.

log(Salary) =5.875 + 0.939 log(POSS) + 0.116 Age + 0.054 USG%
+ 0.078 DBPM 3.424 FGA% (03 ft) + 0.07 ORB% 2.482 FGA% (310 ft)
+ 0.554 FG% (310 ft) 0.047 FTAr 0.104 Avg Shot Dist + 0.001 Age USG%


Compared to the raw salary model, this log-transformed version includes a notably different set of predictors. I opted to use log(POSS) rather than raw possessions after observing that it provided a better linear fit and helped reduce heteroskedasticity, a common issue when modeling right-skewed variables like salary. Other additions like Average Shot Distance and short-range shooting metrics offered insight into shot selection and scoring efficiency near the rim. With an adjusted R of 0.708, this model explains a substantial portion of the variance in player salary (in log terms). Its important to interpret the coefficients accordingly: since the dependent variable is log-transformed, a one-unit increase in any predictor corresponds to a multiplicative (percentage-based) change in salary rather than an absolute one. This makes the model more interpretable when comparing relative impact across features, especially for lower-paid players or those on varying contract scales.


Overall, the log-transformed model provides a useful alternative to the raw salary approach by offering a more statistically stable and interpretable frameworkparticularly when evaluating proportional differences in salary outcomes. While it does not outperform the raw model in terms of mean absolute error or adjusted R, its ability to reduce skew and isolate relative impact makes it valuable in certain analytical contexts. For example, this version is well-suited for comparing players across contract tiers or evaluating changes in value across time. Ultimately, while the raw salary model may be slightly stronger for precise salary prediction, the log model offers cleaner residual patterns and may be more appropriate for understanding percentage-based influences on compensation. Depending on the specific applicationwhether forecasting dollar value or explaining variationeither model has merit.

Model 3 - Percentile-Based Salary

For the third modeling approach, I shifted from predicting absolute salary values to predicting a players percentile rank within the overall salary distribution. This method provides a relative measure of a players market value compared to their peers, rather than focusing solely on the dollar amount. Predicting salary percentile can be particularly useful when comparing players across seasons, different contract environments, or varying salary cap conditions, as it inherently adjusts for broader shifts in the leagues financial landscape. It also opens up the ability to rank and tier players more flexibly, rather than relying strictly on raw figures that may fluctuate heavily from year to year.

To build the model, I again used linear regression on player-level stats, but with salary percentilescaled from 0 to 100as the target variable instead of salary itself. As with the earlier models, I performed both forward and backward subset selection to find the most impactful predictors. After training the initial model, I applied outlier filtering based on leverage, standardized residuals, and Cooks distance to clean the data and improve model robustness. The final version aims to explain how certain on-court production metricslike usage, efficiency, and playmakingrelate to a players salary standing among NBA point guards. The resulting cleaned model formula is shown below:

Salary Percentile =-0.984 + 0 POSS + 0.027 Age + 0.013 USG%
+ 0.013 DBPM 0.402 FGA% (310 ft) + 0.388 FG% (310 ft) + 0.089 BLK%
+ 0.006 AST%


After fitting the model and cleaning for outliers, the percentile-based salary model achieved a mean absolute error of approximately 44.4 percentile points on the test set. The model also produced a strong adjusted R of 0.702, indicating that it explains a substantial portion of the variance in salary rankings among point guards. Given that percentile predictions inherently focus on relative position rather than exact dollar amounts, this model offers a useful and interpretable way to evaluate player standing within the salary hierarchy. In the next visual, I further assess how well the predicted and actual percentiles align across the player sample.


The overall performance of the percentile-based salary model highlights important connections between a point guards statistical profile and their standing within the NBA salary hierarchy. Positive coefficients for metrics like Usage Rate (USG%), Field Goal Percentage (310 ft), and Assist Rate (AST%) reflect the high value placed on guards who can not only handle a heavy offensive load but also create for themselves and others efficiently in the midrange and close to the riman area traditionally important for smaller guards navigating traffic in the paint. Conversely, negative coefficients on stats like DBPM (defensive box plus-minus) and short-range FGA rates suggest that point guards whose impact skews heavily defensive or who struggle finishing at the rim may be relatively less valued from a salary perspective, especially compared to offensive versatility. The plot above further shows that while there is some spread, particularly in the lower salary ranges, the model captures a strong overall relationship between predicted and actual standing. The LOESS curve tracks upward in a reasonably aligned manner, suggesting the model is effective at separating higher-paid guards from lower-paid ones based on statistical contributions. Ultimately, this model provides a nuanced lens into how play style, scoring zones, and usage patterns shape a point guards market value in todays NBA.

Comparative Analysis of Salary Models

Across the three modeling approachesraw salary, log-transformed salary, and percentile salarya few key factors consistently emerge as drivers of point guard value. Metrics centered around offensive creation and efficiency are especially important, with variables like Usage Rate (USG%), Offensive Box Plus-Minus (OBPM), and FG% from 310 feet appearing prominently. This aligns well with the expectations for the point guard position: players who can efficiently handle a large offensive load and create opportunities for themselves and others are more highly compensated. Positive coefficients on variables like USG%, short-range shooting efficiency, and even AST% in the percentile model suggest that assertive offensive playmaking and finishing touch close to the rim elevate a point guards value. Interestingly, Turnover Rate (TOV%) showed a small positive coefficient in the raw salary model, which may indicate that players entrusted with high usage rolesdespite occasional mistakesstill command strong salaries based on their overall offensive responsibility. Additionally, defensive impact, measured through Block Percentage (BLK%), surfaced positively in multiple models, reflecting how supplemental defensive contributions can provide added value even for guards. On the other hand, some variables displayed negative coefficients, such as FGA% from 03 feet and Average Shot Distance in the log-salary model. These results suggest that poor finishing efficiency around the basket or an overreliance on longer jump shots can slightly lower a point guards market value, emphasizing the premium placed on efficient scoring inside and smart shot selection.

From a modeling perspective, I chose linear regression combined with subset selection because it offers a strong balance between interpretability, parsimony, and statistical efficiency. NBA salary data, especially when focused narrowly on a single position like point guards, is prone to noise from external factors like team fit, market size, and injuries. Building linear models while using forward and backward subset selection helped isolate the variables most strongly tied to compensation without overfitting the data. This approach made it easier to trace how specific statistical strengthssuch as shot creation efficiency, possession usage, and complementary defensive skillstranslate into salary outcomes. While each model (raw, log-transformed, percentile) offered slightly different framing on player value, together they emphasize that in todays NBA, point guards who can create, score efficiently at multiple levels, limit inefficiencies around the rim, and impact the game beyond just scoring are the ones most rewarded financially.

The table above provides a side-by-side comparison of the three cleaned models across key evaluation metrics. While each approach has clear strengths, the log-transformed salary model ultimately emerges as the most balanced and effective. Although its mean absolute error is slightly higher than the raw salary model, the log model offers greater scale robustness, stronger residual patterns, and lower multicollinearity among predictors, which is critical for building stable, interpretable models. The predictor setcentered around possession load (log(POSS)), age, and short-range shot attempt share (FGA% 03 feet)aligns more logically with true player usage and offensive role, offering a cleaner explanation of point guard salary drivers. Meanwhile, the raw salary model, despite a strong adjusted R, showed some oddities: factors like 2PT and 3PT shooting percentages had negative coefficients, and turnover percentage (TOV%) appeared with a positive coefficient, both of which run counter to typical expectations about player value. By stabilizing salary outcomes and tying predictors more closely to real basketball traits, the log-transformed model provides a more reliable and analytically sound foundation for evaluating point guard compensation across different salary tiers.

Applying the Model: Player Evaluation and Insights

In this section, I apply the log-transformed salary model to evaluate specific player seasons and assess how closely their actual earnings aligned with their statistical production. By comparing predicted salaries to real-world contracts, I can identify cases where the model suggests a player may have been overpaid, underpaid, or fairly compensated relative to their on-court performance. This provides a practical way to test the models effectiveness while highlighting real examples where player value may have exceeded or fallen short of market expectations.

Darius Garland 2023/24 Season
In the 202324 season, Darius Garland entered the first year of his five-year designated rookie extension, earning approximately $34 million. However, based on his statistical production, the model predicted a salary of just under $8 milliononly about 23% of his actual earnings. Garland appeared in only 57 games that year, the fewest since his rookie season, and posted declines in several key areas compared to previous seasons. His scoring dropped to 18.0 points per game, down from 21.6 the year before, and his 3-point percentage fell to 37.1%, his lowest since his second year in the league. His assist numbers also dipped to 6.5 assists per game, while his turnover rate remained relatively high at 3.1 turnovers per game. Although he maintained decent shooting efficiency overall (44.6% FG, 83.4% FT), the drop in volume, playmaking, and overall impact relative to his hefty salary was significant. The model effectively captured this underperformance, offering a clear monetary perspective on how Garlands production in 202324 did not align with the value of a max contract point guard.

Reggie Jackson 2023/24 Season
In the 202324 season, Reggie Jackson signed a modest two-year deal with the Denver Nuggets, earning around $5 million for the year. However, based on his statistical output, the model projected a value closer to $19.5 millionnearly four times his actual salary. Jackson appeared in 72 games, providing consistent minutes off the bench with 19.9 minutes per game, and delivered 10.2 points and 3.8 assists per game. His shooting splits were strong for a veteran guard, posting 43.1% from the field and 35.2% from three, while maintaining low turnover numbers (1.3 per game). Despite a lower overall role compared to his prime years, Jacksons efficient scoring, steady playmaking, and ball security made him a highly valuable depth piece on a contending team. The model accurately reflected how his contributions, relative to his small salary, were extremely cost-effective, highlighting an underappreciated veteran season.

Recap

Working on this project has been a fun experience. I enjoyed diving deep into NBA data, building models, creating visualizations, and finding ways to better understand how player salaries align with their on-court performance. Throughout this project, I learned a lot about improving model selection, communicating insights through visuals, and building cleaner, more structured code. This project could be improved by using the model to predict what annual salary that player then deserves given their past on-court metrics. Additionally, incorparting team-based success and metrics into the model would defintely help to improve accuracy and fit.

Looking ahead, I plan to continue developing projects like this by expanding the types of metrics considered, exploring deeper predictive modeling techniques, and making my visual storytelling even stronger. I welcome any feedback or suggestions on how I can continue to grow in this space.
